org.jawin
Class Variant

java.lang.Object
  org.jawin.Variant
public class Variant
extends java.lang.Object

The Jawin equivalent of the Windows Variant type.

Important: VERY expensive to instantiate in terms of memory.

Contains also some intrinsics static methods for marshalling.

Version:
$Revision: 1.9 $
Author:
Stuart Halloway, http://www.relevancellc.com/halloway/weblog/

Method Detail

writeObject

public static void writeObject(java.lang.Object var,
                               LittleEndianOutputStream leos)
                        throws COMException
marshall an object onto an output stream. The object will be marshalled following these rules (please notice that primitive types should be wrapped in their wrapper types, eg. int should be Integer - this should not usually be done for arrays though, see below):
  • null: will be marshalled to VT_NULL
  • instanceof Variant.ByrefHolder: will be marshalled as the base type + VT_BYREF.
  • array-types: will be marshalled as the base type + VT_ARRAY (and VT_BYREF if the array was wrapped in a Variant.ByrefHolder).
  • Byte: will be marshalled as VT_UI1.
  • Short: will be marshalled as VT_I2.
  • Integer: will be marshalled as VT_I4.
  • Long: will be marshalled as VT_I8.
  • Float: will be marshalled as VT_R4.
  • Double: will be marshalled as VT_R8.
  • instanceof Date: will be marshalled as VT_DATE and will be converted using DateUtil.getWin32Date(java.util.Date).
  • Boolean: will be marshalled as VT_BOOL.
  • String: will be marshalled as VT_BSTR.
  • instanceof Variant: will be marshalled as a VT_VARIANT using the value of the vt-property. Please note that VT_VARIANT MUST be combined with VT_BYREF.
  • instanceof DispatchPtr: will be marshalled as VT_DISPATCH.
  • instanceof UnknownPtr: will be marshalled as VT_UNKNOWN.
If none of the rules match, a COMException will be thrown.

Notice that the IDispatch coercion mechanism handles scenarios where the VT_TYPE of the parameters is a not a 100% fit to a method signature. Therefore there should not be any problems by calling eg. a method requering unsigned int's with either a Long or an Integer.

Arrays: If writing an array, the primitive types should generally be used and not the wrapper classes. Eg. 
	var = new int[]{ 7, 9, 13 };
is correct, whereas 
	var = new Integer[]{ new Integer(7) , new Integer(9) , new Integer(13) };
is not.

One should consult the section on array-marshalling in docs/jawinuserguide_dispatch.html for how the different Java-arrays are marshalled.

Arrays of objects will be written as an VT_VARIANT|VT_ARRAY where each element will be written following the rules mentioned above.

For this reason it is also believed that multidimensional arrays will be marshalled into a SafeArray on the native side containing other SafeArrays and NOT multidimensional SafeArrays (TODO: This has not been tested and should be verified, and perhaps the code should be instrumentable, so it can be controlled to map multidimensional java-arrays into multimensional SafeArrays on the native side).

The marshalling code is the "inverse" of the native code in the method deserializeVariant() in Transform.cpp

Parameters:
var - the object to write to the stream.
leos - the stream the object should be written to.
Throws:
COMException - if the object can not be marshalled due to invalid type or due to IOExceptions on the stream.

readObject

public static java.lang.Object readObject(LittleEndianInputStream leis)
                                   throws COMException
unmarshall an object from an input stream. The object will be unmarshalled following these rules:
  • VT_EMPTY and VT_NULL: will be unmarshalled as null.
  • *|VT_BYREF: will be unmarshalled as the base VT_TYPE, ie. the returned object will NOT be wrapped in a Variant.ByrefHolder.
  • *|VT_ARRAY: will be unmarshalled as an array of the base type.
  • VT_I1 and VT_UI1: will be unmarshalled as Byte.
  • VT_I2 and VT_UI2: will be unmarshalled as Short.
  • VT_I4, VT_UI4, VT_INT, VT_UINT and VT_ERROR: will be unmarshalled as Integer.
  • VT_I8, VT_UI8 and VT_CY: will be unmarshalled as Long.
  • VT_R4: will be unmarshalled as Float.
  • VT_R8: will be unmarshalled as Double.
  • VT_DATE: will be unmarshalled as Date using the DateUtil.getJavaDate(double)-method.
  • VT_BOOL: will be unmarshalled as Boolean.
  • VT_BSTR: will be unmarshalled as String.
  • VT_VARIANT: will be unmarshalled as the wrapped base object, ie. will NOT be returned as a Variant-object.
  • VT_DISPATCH: will be unmarshalled as a DispatchPtr-object.
  • VT_UNKNOWN: will be unmarshalled as a UnknownPtr-object.
If none of the rules match, a COMException will be thrown.

Arrays: If the next object on the input stream is an object, this call will unmarshall the entire array. If it is an array of primitive types it will be returned as such (and NOT as an array of the wrapper class). Eg. if the next object on the stream is an int-array: 
	int[] result = (int[])Variant.readObject(leis);


The unmarshalling code is the "inverse" of the native code in the method serializeVariant() in Transform.cpp

Parameters:
leis - the stream the object should be read from.
Returns:
the next object on the stream.
Throws:
COMException - if the object can not be unmarshalled due to an unknown VT_TYPE or due to IOExceptions on the stream.
